The architects looked in - the office also has a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furnishings, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architecture firm Arch.Design, from whose studios a whole range of well-known Brno buildings originated, calculated from the very first designs for the new Avriopoint building on the premises for its corporate mini-kindergarten.
Wise foresight, because most of its 90 staff are baby boomers, and the company is keen for the project- and architects to return to work as quickly as possible.
Along with being able to work shortened, kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for the building engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding careers and child care.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design. With the support of management, they succeeded in winning grants from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company's mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from funds of the European Social Fund and from the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (grants of CZK 2.8 million) it was possible to procure the necessary facilities and equipment. Qualified personnel and operation is provided for a duration of 2 years.
After the funds have been exhausted (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue running the mini-kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
Preparing this project took an entire year, with the Economy Rating company providing active assistance in application processing.
Children are looked after full-time by qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher. Children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at a time, however, alternate throughout the day across multiple children.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly tuned to the needs of the parents. The children of all employees have the same rights regarding the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is about individual education and care, the contents of the program at the mini-kindergarten are nevertheless comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
The children are not only playing here. Above all, they are provided with excellent instruction - from basic knowledge to pre-school instruction, along the way they learn English as well.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a calculator available to the children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can have a look at the children at any time. This eliminates the stress of late pick-up of children from a far-flung kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also formed here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that provide significant benefits when recruiting new employees. These benefits are family-friendly, and they empower their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house is still fascinating after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase looks like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are ripped open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló designed by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname & quot; Bonehead & quot;.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splints and mosaics, the shed-like façades and ubiquitous soft lines. These are all typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures that recall nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection can one notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm, and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole facade looks even more three-dimensional, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the brilliance of the colours even more.
The same sweeping lines and intertwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy shaped timber copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, yes even peepholes and moldings.
The Batlló house, located in the Eixample neighbourhood on the busy Passeig de Grácia no. 43 shopping street, was created through the reconstruction of an 1877 house, carried out by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
Reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one. But in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batlló apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked together with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative dwelling of the owner of reality were created. Also the use of mosaics on the façade was his idea.
However, numerous other visual artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
Working together on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Güell Park, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Already shortly after its completion the house got the nickname & quot; bone house from the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the & quot; yawning house & quot;.
It is also said that at the very top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolise hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house at the time with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree inclination already sounds a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of that time and by no means succumbed to them.
Before construction started, he did obtain the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city's fathers were so appalled by the result when it was completed two years later that they demanded a remedy.
Among other things, the councillors clashed with the fact that the building, with its pillars, even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, changes have not been made. On the contrary, just fifteen days after the neighborhood's request to this effect, Josep Batlló submitted an application for authorization to lease the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social room, on the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor has been leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building passes through a staircase up to the rooftop.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines, replacing them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of connecting spaces together.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors, and so a larger company could chat comfortably without having to forego a certain intimacy for more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors as a result of Gaudí's conversion, apart from a new facade.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with light, as well as the blue and white glazed tiles that cover the courtyard and the courtyards of light.
The play of these two colours gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was inscribed into the World Heritage List by UNESCO in 2005, can be visited by everyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and sumptuous apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was realized that this is a fairly lucrative business, the viewings were retained. In fact, they were also extended to further common and attic rooms, including the rooftop.
The price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard box, however. It is 16.50 euros. Students, retirees, groups and holders of tourist cards get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get acquainted with the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon turrets, you should try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
