This is said to be related to the levels of the male hormone testosterone.
& quot; our results show that the relative length of fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer. & quot; does this especially in men up to sixty, & quot; co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
