In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues pursued more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer in the UK, but at the same time, they also followed 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study's participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same probability of developing prostate cancer as 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were of the same length.
However, for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, compared to 87 percent for men up to sixty.
The ratio of length of the two mentioned fingers, which already form at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones the child was exposed to in the uterus.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
