The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is support for private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These results were generated by the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, thus showing the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts fall particularly in & apo;'s eye in this year' s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
, and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its principal institutions.
In numerous countries on the Pacific coast of South America, the democratic movement has increased greatly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by approximately 6% per year since 2002, the number of pro-democracy workers increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy is recovering since last year's sharp slump.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, lowering the regional average (see chart, 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practices. This is the same as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase over 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts at greater democracy.
That this persisted even during the Great Depression may be because the countries of Latin America experienced only a brief period of recession, and recovered rapidly.
In addition, the poor were absorbed by a stronger social safety net.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission on Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong mood differences from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva' s popularity is reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more acute and violent crime has increased.
It is only the second time since the survey began that many respondents in Latin America consider crime in their country to be a greater problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member have been victims of a crime in the past year. However, down from 38% in the last year, values have fallen, reaching their lowest level since 1995.
Increasing economic performance is reflected in the increased support for private and market economies. Approximately 71% of respondents nationally said private sector is indispensable to development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of private enterprise), though their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is nationalizing many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
By contrast, respondents in Mexico and most countries in Central America consider the US to be the most influential country. This role is assumed by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
