The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that may live on, among others, arsenic, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously deemed vital.
& quot; This organism has two possibilities. & quot;
& quot; It requires either phosphorus or arsenic to grow. & quot;
& quot; This makes it very special, although it is almost a kind of & apos; alien & apos; life form, & quot;, said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which will appear Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphor, and sulfur.
However, as the scientists discovered, the bacterium in Mono Lake, California, continues to grow even when it replaces phosphor with arsenic.
& quot; It makes you wonder what else is possible & quot; said the report's co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details about the discovery were released gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery of & quot; shows that in other planetary systems, organisms with the help of other elements can initiate biochemical processes, and that the & apos; standard elements of & apos;, which we believe are absolutely vital to life, are not necessarily fixed, said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
& quot; This work is a novelty, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another, & quot; added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorous are chemically alike, she assumed that microbes exposed to both could possibly replace one element with the other.
& quot; The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus. & quot;
& quot; This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other. & quot;
& quot; But the difference is so big that arsenic acts differently from phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system where it smears virtually everything & quot; explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
The microbe grows better in phosphor, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
According to Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorous can be replaced with arsenic is not new. But, so far, there has been no functioning example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
& quot; This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently from the early Earth age & quot;, said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
