Can civility connect the divider?
After a campaign of swear words and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of true two-party cooperation, or a moment of illusion before quickly returning to the parties' struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders failed to produce a breakthrough on the big issues to deal with during the so-called & quot; lame duck session & quot;, the session at the end of a government period where no decisions are made.
From what you hear, governing was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility. Rather, it was an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The public meeting of the president's deficit commission on Wednesday was likewise civilized, despite the political differences that persist between members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that masks the ideological divide that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - with one demanding signs of willingness to cooperate and compromise from the other, while trying to balance the boundaries of public opinion and voters' patience after another partisan war.
Therefore, Tuesday's meeting itself and its evaluation by the attendees were limited to a minimum of demands or recrimination.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Regardless of whether it is about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November election has, for at least a short time, softened Washington.
& quot; No doubt, the tone has changed & quot;, said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the & quot; Ethics and Public Policy Center & quot;.
& quot; This is unavoidable after elections.
Elections reawaken partisan passions that die away again.
And that's fine. & quot;
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the & quot; lame duck session & quot;, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution. & quot;
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is advocating them.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, be it temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise can be expected on the increased unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich will be believed while denying assistance to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is an increased optimism that during the & quot; lame duck session & quot; it is possible to agree on these issues, while at the same time ratifying the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the lame duck session & quot; may not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of non-match is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
& quot; After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation, & quot; said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
& quot; I see much that is happening from now until 2012, as a pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012 & quot;, he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with putting up the new Republican majority in the White House, and with the tea party voters who helped their formation.
However concerned Republican leaders may be about playing too much poker, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and undo health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial responses to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and cutting government spending.
The vice chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington, and, by their own estimation, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes inside the commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling a lot to even get close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the board, because on financial issues, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston is predicting two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans will challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes and the health care system, followed later by a period of major bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It has been proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, a majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, then both parties need to be careful of the public response.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek the compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than it was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more consequentially far-reaching election 2012.
Viewed this way, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will require much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator on the issues that still divide them.
