China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
China's representative told COP16 that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints, and that he would maintain his offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China considers its offer to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the representative of this country at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei asserted that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and to convert its industry.
He said that in the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its targets, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China's strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and pilot program support.
Progress has been made on all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy bill last year that includes the targets for reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states had worked together with those of the central and local governments to achieve the goals of saving energy, using energy effectively and reducing emissions.
Furthermore, he pointed out, some multi-year plans have already been started or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government, and those that received funding from other countries.
For example, he was referring to the Effective Use of Energy Program, which was introduced in the last five years and had received investment from the United Nations (UN), government, and private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, a government science adviser on climate change in that country, acknowledged that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly assumed.
He pointed out that the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy usage. Energy efficiency has been increased by twenty percent over the last five years, and another one is due to happen by 2020, he explained.
