The USA changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must introduce themselves before their interview at the consulate at the visa application service offices; costs waiting times are thus shortened.
From 10 January 2011 onwards, the procedures for applying for a visa will change at the United States Embassy and at the Consulates.
Under the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves prior to their interview in the consulate at the Visa Application Services (ASC, the initial letters are in English).
ASC staff records the applicant's biometric data, which will be reviewed by the Consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, these include:
The total cost of visa processing is decreasing because it is no longer required to pay separately for scheduling, processing the visa application and the transportation service used to hand out the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for handlers and investors.
Those who only wish to extend their visa do not need to hold a conversation at the consulate. They only need to introduce themselves at the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
As the biometric data is collected at the ASC, those applicants who need a second appointment at the Consulate for the interview will be left with less time than before.
Those applying for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer need to pay the $26 service charge.
For additional information about the new visa application procedure, please visit the following web site: http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs.html
