Worldwide Lighting Renewal Plan
In Cancun yesterday, the UN proposed a plan to renew lighting in homes, trade and industry in 100 countries, with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (CFCs), equivalent to almost one-third of the additional reduction that must be achieved to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun, to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from the developed countries.
Under the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem, in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs emitted due to light exposure to the Earth would be avoided if the incandescent white light bulbs, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better yet, light emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the worldwide fleet of vehicles.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans, designed to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
From this balance, however, one would still have to deduct 5 Gt to stabilize the 2 degree Celsius rise in climate from now until 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
The compact fluorescent bulbs reduce the energy consumption by 75%. With the new LED light bulbs you reduce this energy requirement by a further twofold.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10.000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as the ones launched this week by manufacturer Philips - this company, incidentally, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb. This gives a hint of the savings possibilities of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
Besides the fact that these completely new type of light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also function with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury, and that one must therefore dispose of them as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the producers provide an acceptance point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power stations, which emit much more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year by purchasing electricity and eight million tons of CO2. This means the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power stations would cost Indonesia $2.5 billion to build.
