Vengeful hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a dual meaning.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal. A scandal that is merely a scandal of sinister hypocrisy that governs the relations between the states, the citizens, and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at an international level, and gives a taste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's move forward in sequence.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the acknowledgement of the fact that every file created by an intelligence service (of any nation) is made up entirely of newspaper cuttings.
The & quot; extraordinary & quot;, American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what was read for months anyway in any journal (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gadhafi' s alarmingly caricatured profile has long provided comedy artists with material for their sketches.
The rule according to which the secret files can only exist of news that is already known is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go into a library devoted to esotherical publications, you will recognize that each work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosary) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish any research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult do not believe in anything other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Likewise the secret file.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) is also the head of the Secret Service (otherwise, he might be whatever, for example, editor at Libération), who considers only what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had already published the week before.
So why has such a fuss been made about the disclosures in these files?
On one page, these state what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then, the Heads of State or Government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few minor representational tasks, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy to pretend to ignore this.
Still, the fact of repeating it in public hurts the task of hypocrisy, and serves to paint American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that a once-in-a-generation hacker can tap into the most secretive secrets of the world's most powerful country is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
What's more, the scandal puts the victims in distress rather than the & quot; executioners.
But let's address the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's day, you could bundle all power like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel you visited, the chosen highway, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But when you consider what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape a hacker's control, the control process ceases to be biased and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can experience the secrets of power.
But how can a power hold that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi's or Merkel' s character is basically a secret free from secrecy, since it divulges the public sphere; but to reveal, WikiLeaks-style, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to strip them of any power.
WikiLeaks did not do wrong to Sarkozy or to Merkel; it did wrong to Clinton and Obama.
What will the consequences of this insult, which has been inflicted on such a mighty power?
It's obvious that states will no longer put any reserved information online in the future - that would be tantamount to a notice stuck on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the current technologies it is futile to hope to be able to keep confidential reports about phone secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a leader of state moves around in an airplane and has contacted one of his or her colleagues.
How could certain relationships be maintained in the future, both private and for certain ears only?
I am well aware that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romantic, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, moving in secret ways, busily, along uncontrollable itineraries, carrying their communications nowhere else but in bare memory, and furthermore, hiding the little written information they have received, in the shoe heel.
The information would be stored in locked drawers in a single copy: basically, Watergate's espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks'.
I had the opportunity to write that today's technology is advancing like a cancer, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph using (telephone) wire.
The (analog) videocassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by being able to rewind from back to front and unearth all the secrets of the montage, whereas the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, in macro proportions.
With the high-speed trains, you can travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, including the transfer, this takes you three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to the car and horse.
One final observation.
In earlier times the press tried to understand what kind of secrets were forged between the messages.
Currently, it is the messages that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France whitewashes its financial promises
A year after the Copenhagen accord, it is time to examine the fulfillment of the fast-solved financing promises (also called & quot; Fast start & quot; or premature financing) implemented by developing countries.
And already the rough French goodies are revealed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised €7.2 billion over three years, while France has promised €1.26 billion (ie; €420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed procedure report of its member states, press conference, major fringe events, brochure distribution.
The Transparency operation is remarkable, and grades appreciated for its real value: developing countries and civil society would love it if all developed countries did the same thing at the same precision level.
The EU announces to have released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track towards respecting its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look into the details, things are a bit more complicated.
This money, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, & quot; should be new and additional to & quot; to ensure that an additional deployment was brought in without prejudice to Official Development Assistance.
Sorry, there is no consensus on what & quot; means new and additionally & quot;.
While the EU Commission had proposed a harmonisation, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today everyone chooses the guideline they consider to be the best.
The EU Commission has chosen, for example, as an indicative for the 2009 one: international funding will be retained, adding $150 million over three years as part of the funding for & quot; Fast-start & quot;.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of ODA.
In return, France was of the opinion that the financing of all new & quot; projects for the year 2010 was & quot; new and in addition to & quot;.
In other words, there are no indicative figures for the previous year's expenditure, or at the global level of Official Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of French assistance to developing countries can remain stable (or decreases) - France pretends to abide by its commitment regarding the & quot; new and additional & quot; funding.
Another key element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on that yet, and everyone chooses his arithmetic mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 borrowed €as equivalent with 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often carbon-containment projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro you are collecting as the equivalent of a donated euro... Also, only the cost of the loan for the donor country of capital should be counted as a commitment (i. e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind but the following consideration: it & quot; respects & quot; its obligation of 420 million Euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million Euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million Euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only EU country to use loans on a large scale.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) follow up their obligations with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents, understanding a comparable stake.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France is operating with a double hoax in its near-start financing: one part with an evolution of the action over time and the other part with the reality of the financial deployment.
France succeeds in making us believe that it has spent 420 million & quot; new and additional & quot; million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros in the process.
The manipulation of the finance ministry (since it probably seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could result in a doubly negative effect; once intra-EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries cannot be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question on relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it might be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that will not be the case.
Either way, it is imperative to learn his lesson from that first year of premature funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance the discussions on the subject of the dispute of long-term financing (another, crucial, and currently debated). You cannot escape the issue of & quot; creditability & quot; or the type of accounting on its loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive on issues of contention as it is on other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast-start of France and its vision of the & quot; accountability & quot; as well as use of loans would by nature raise the international trust base necessary for further discussion.
